description_PD: The addition of nanosilica into SMP resins enables superior shape recovery performance, maintaining a high recovery ratio of 87-90%, which is crucial for designing products that retain or revert to their original shape after deformation.

The tunable shape-shifting behavior of the shape memory polymers (SMPs) enables the creation of complex 3D geometries that can dynamically change their form, unlocking new design possibilities for intelligent devices.

The 4D-printed NiTi shape-memory alloys (SMAs) exhibit phase transformation-driven shape-shifting behaviors, allowing designers to create smart structures that respond dynamically to environmental changes.

The in situ 4D printing process enables synchronous shape formation and property enhancement through time-dependent precipitation hardening, allowing designers to create high-strength structures with integrated functionality changes.
The 4D textile composite self-forms and changes its shape under thermal stimulation, allowing designers to create smart, adaptive products with dynamic shape-shifting properties.
The re-entrant honeycomb auxetic grids exhibit tunable shape-shifting behavior, allowing for dynamic transformations over time, making it ideal for designing complex, responsive geometries.

The flexible anisotropic soft-magnetic composite (FASMC) exhibits controlled motion and deformation under an external magnetic field, enabling the design of smart sensors, actuators, and robots with precise and responsive shape-shifting behaviors.

The PETG-ABS-Fe3O4 nanocomposites demonstrate advanced shape-shifting abilities, enabled by magnetic and heat-induced stimuli, allowing for innovative designs that can change shape remotely and adapt to various applications, especially in 4D printing.

The PETG-PBAT blends exhibit excellent shape recovery with increased PBAT content, enabling faster and more efficient shape-shifting behavior, which enhances the design possibilities for complex 4D printed objects.
The design of the 4D printed structure leverages the thermal expansion and contraction properties of PVC-PP composites to achieve the desired shape-shifting behavior.

description_PE: The nanosilica particles dramatically reduce the curing time from 4 seconds to 0.7 seconds per layer, greatly accelerating the printing process and improving manufacturing efficiency.

The digital light fabrication process enhances elongation properties of SMPs, allowing precise control over material flexibility and expansion during the 4D printing process, achieving elongation up to 250%.

The NiTi alloy's elongation properties, achieved through the partitioned repetitive laser scanning (PRS) strategy, enable controlled deformation and recovery during manufacturing, ensuring enhanced mechanical performance.

The in situ Ni3Ti precipitation in the martensitic matrix during deposition improves mechanical properties like tensile strength and elongation, optimizing the additive manufacturing process for high-performance steel parts without post heat treatment.

The varying thickness of PLA and the relative elongation of Lycra fabric allow precise control over the material’s permanent and temporary shapes, optimizing the 4D printing process for consistent, reliable elongation behavior.

The auxetic grids can undergo decoupled in-plane elongation and out-of-plane bending, offering precise control over deformation and recovery during the 4D printing process, enabling more flexible and adaptable production workflows.

The FASMC demonstrates excellent elongation up to 460%, balancing tensile strength and printability during the manufacturing process, making it suitable for additive manufacturing with magnetic field-assisted digital light processing (MF-DLP).

The nanocomposites show a reduction in elongation with increasing Fe3O4 content, highlighting the balance between tensile strength and elongation that must be managed during the manufacturing process to ensure optimal mechanical performance and print quality.

The elongation properties of the PETG-PBAT composites, particularly with 30% PBAT, provide flexibility and toughness, allowing for better mechanical performance and adaptability during and after the printing process.
The composite material’s elongation properties, particularly in the 50%PVC-50%PP blend, ensure robust mechanical performance during the 3D printing process and post-print recovery.

description_MS: The nanosilica-reinforced SMP composites exhibit a significant increase in elongation (up to 85.2%), demonstrating enhanced mechanical flexibility and strength, which are critical for creating durable and responsive 4D printed materials.

The spatio-temporal tuning of shape memory transition temperature and rubbery modulus in SMPs facilitates molecular transformations, enabling fine control over the material's ability to recover its original shape after deformation.

The laser-tuned phase transformation between the B2 and B19' phases in NiTi SMAs drives the material’s shape memory and mechanical properties, resulting in a responsive 4D-printed structure with enhanced strength and adaptability.

The novel Fe-Ni-Ti-Al steel undergoes molecular-level transformations through heterogeneous nucleation and dislocation-driven precipitation, enhancing material properties and enabling time-dependent changes in structure during laser additive manufacturing.

The thermal responsiveness of the PLA-Lycra composite drives the material’s ability to expand and contract, enabling reversible transformations between multiple shapes, which are key to the functionality of the 4D textile.

The photopolymer used in the auxetic structures exhibits a Temperature Memory Effect (TME), enabling the material to remember deformation temperature and achieve controlled, hierarchical shape recovery based on thermal stimuli.

The material’s ability to change stiffness under an external magnetic field, due to the anisotropic arrangement of magnetic particles, highlights its potential for next-generation metamaterials and advanced smart applications.

The PETG-ABS-Fe3O4 nanocomposites exhibit enhanced shape memory performance, where the inclusion of iron oxide improves heat transfer and the elastic response, enabling faster and more effective shape recovery under magnetic and thermal stimuli.

The molecular interactions between PETG and PBAT influence the blend's thermomechanical properties, driving phase compatibility and molecular transformations that enhance shape memory performance and mechanical strength in 4D printed structures.
The molecular interactions in PVC-PP composites enable phase compatibility and transformation, driving the material's elongation and shape memory properties in 4D printed structures.
